Title: Cross-polar Anomaly and the Ontology of Degrees  
Author: Christopher Kennedy 
Date: February 1998  
Affiliation: Northwestern University  
Abstract: This paper uses the phenomenon of cross-polar anomalythe anomaly of comparatives constructed out of positive and negative pairs of adjectivesas an empirical basis for two conclusions about the semantic analysis of gradable adjectives. First, abstract representations of measurement, or degrees, must be modelled as intervals on a scale, rather than points on a scale, as traditionally assumed. Second, an empirically and explanatorily adequate semantics for gradable adjectives must introduce degrees into the ontology, since approaches that do not do not make reference to such abstract representations of measurement do not support a principled explanation of cross-polar anomaly. 
